# FTP Server Setup (vsftpd)  

## Objective

To configure an FTP server on a Linux system to enable secure file transfer between multiple users with controlled access.

---

## Tools & Services Used

* Linux (RHEL / CentOS)
* vsftpd (Very Secure FTP Daemon)

---

## Installation

```bash
sudo yum install vsftpd -y
```

---

## Start and Enable Service

```bash
sudo systemctl start vsftpd
sudo systemctl enable vsftpd
```

Check status:

```bash
sudo systemctl status vsftpd
```

---

## Create FTP Users

```bash
sudo useradd ftpuser1
sudo passwd ftpuser1
```

---

## Configure FTP Directory

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /home/ftpuser1/ftp/upload
sudo chmod 750 /home/ftpuser1/ftp
sudo chmod 770 /home/ftpuser1/ftp/upload
```

---

## Configure vsftpd

Edit config file:

```bash
sudo vi /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf
```

Update/add:

```ini
anonymous_enable=NO
local_enable=YES
write_enable=YES
chroot_local_user=YES
allow_writeable_chroot=YES
```

---

## Restart Service

```bash
sudo systemctl restart vsftpd
```

---

## Open Firewall (if enabled)

```bash
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=ftp
sudo firewall-cmd --reload
```

---

## Testing FTP Connection

From client:

```bash
ftp <server-ip>
```

Login using created user credentials.

---

## 📊 Result

* FTP server successfully configured
* Multiple users can securely upload/download files
* Access restricted using permissions

---

## Real-World Use Case

Used in organizations for:

* Internal file sharing
* Backup transfers
* Secure data exchange between servers
